[{"id":"VR718695","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows the graph of a sinusoidal wave in the first and fourth quadrants of a gridded plane. The horizontal axis is labeled “time, in seconds,” and the numbers 0 through 1.0, in increments of 0.5, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled “x, in centimeters,” and the numbers negative 4 through 4, in increments of 2, are indicated. The wave begins at 0 seconds and 0 centimeters and moves upward and to the right reaching its first peak at 0.25 seconds comma 3 centimeters and then begins to move back down and to the right crossing the horizontal axis at 0.5 seconds and reaches a trough at 0.75 seconds comma negative 3 centimeters and then begins to move back up to the right crossing over the horizontal axis again at 1.0 second.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR718695.g02.svg\"/></div></div></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A block is placed on a horizontal surface and attached to one end of a spring. The other end of the spring is attached to a fixed wall. The block oscillates such that its <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></math></span></span>-position is described by the graph shown. Starting at time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t equals 2 seconds\"><math alttext=\"t equals 2 seconds\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><mtext>s</mtext></math></span></span>, an external force <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F equals F sub 0 times the cosine of, open parenthesis, 2 pi t, close parenthesis, i hat\"><math alttext=\"F equals F sub 0 times the cosine of, open parenthesis, 2 pi t, close parenthesis, i hat\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>cos</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>i</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></math></span></span>, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"F sub 0\"><math alttext=\"F sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>F</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> is a positive constant, is applied to the block. Which of the following best describes how the block’s motion changes, if at all, when the external force is being applied?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR718695_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The period of the motion increases, and the amplitude of the motion remains the same.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The period of the motion remains the same, and the amplitude of the motion increases.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both the period and the amplitude of the motion increase.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both the period and the amplitude of the motion remain the same.</p>"],"answer":1}]